<font color="#FF0000">SECOND PARADOX</font><br>
<tt>Mon Jan  5 16:28:09 US/Eastern 1998
</tt><p>
Actually, my statement indicates the existence of another paradox.  Let me try to break it down into its possibilities.<br><br>
If we assume that the protesters who claim that the Vietnam War was fundamentally wrong and belongs in a class with the worst of the colonial wars waged by the European powers or even with the Nazi offensive in Europe, then we must conclude that all Americans were obliged to do everything in their power to stop it and undo whatever harm it had caused. If I understand some of the protesters, this is exactly their point of view.<br>
If their view is correct, then every civilian who made decisions that contributed to our loss in Vietnam and every member of the armed forces who failed to do the duty that was expected of him in the war must be viewed as a hero.  Thus, a commander who failed to follow orders, who failed to cooperate with his fellow officers, who permitted chaotic conditions to develop within his command, or who even caused the troops in his command to suffer unnecessary casualties can now come forward as a hero because he hurt the American war effort and contribute to the failure of an unjust cause.<br>
Ironically, Lt. Calley can aspire to hero status because the My Lai massacre did untold damage to the moral standing of the American armed forces and contributed substantially to the loss of public support for the South Vietnamese cause. Exactly this kind of hero status is what Robert McNamara aspires to since he has clearly identified himself with the doves, claiming to have been against the war all along.  I think that even the protesters might find this a little hard to swallow in view of his role in American involvement.<br>
Under these circumstances, it would be incongruous for any American government agency or the Armed Forces themselves to try to find out who failed in their duties and caused us to lose the war.  This would give the person the option of claiming hero status, of claiming that he knew that the war was immoral and was therefore working from within to make sure that it did not succeed.  Hence, whether it is a defense contractor who sold defective weapons, a CIA agent who actively worked against the war he was being paid to support and falsified intelligence information on the demand of his superiors, a reconnaissance pilot who flew over the beach instead of looking for the enemy about to attack American troops, a general who spent his time enriching himself with bribes from black marketeers, a POW who made himself a star of propaganda movies, or just a plain private who fomented racial unrest or hate for the allied Vietnamese within his own unit, he can avoid censure for his dishonorable or disloyal conduct by saying that he was refusing to contribute to an immoral war.<br>
Only if the war is accepted as an evil necessary to avoid greater evil in the form of an expanding communist empire, murderous reprisals against the civilian populations of Vietnam, Cambodia, and Laos which refused to help the communists, and providing an terrible example that governments can be taken over by terror tactics of saboteurs disguising themselves as civilians, can we seriously start looking for the culprits who engineered the defeat.  They can no longer simply say that they were helping the failure of an unjust cause, they were rather bringing about the failure of a just cause through immoral and illegal conduct.<br>
There is another aspect of this problem.  From my own experience, I am convinced that the government, including its armed forces, were guilty of numerous crimes during the Vietnam Era.  These include ordinary Mafia-like activities, such as pocketing millions from slot machines set up in service clubs, receiving enormous bribes for permitting child prostitution on and near military bases, demanding kickbacks from salesmen peddling their wares through the exchange systems, and allowing defective equipment to be passed off on government agencies.  Any time these activities were brought to light, the protesters seized on them as reasons for ending the war.  Although these crimes had nothing to do with the war, the government started making special efforts to cover up any of these activities in order to prevent the protesters from seizing on them as arguments for ending the war.  If there had been no protest movement or if the protesters had separated the war issue from the corruption issue, government prosecuters might have been willing to send the perpetrators off to Federal prison, where they belonged.  However, to keep fuel off the protest fires, many of these crooked officers were simply stuck in some closet until they retired, and the matter was forgotten about.  Gradually, whistle blowers, who should have been given credit for exposing illegal activities, came to be regarded as traitors in government circles because the crimes they exposed brought discredit to the goals the government had set for itself.<br>
Finally, disreputable public officials who were subjected to criticism could often escape censure by claiming that they was just being smeared by the protest movement, some of whose members criticized all public officials and even ordinary military personnel just because they were trying to do their job in the belief that the war they were supporting was a just one.<br>
I hope this explains what I mean.<br>
Incidently, a new book is on the market, unfortunately only in French.  Its title translates, The Black Book of Communism.  The book starts with Lenin and works its way through Mao, Ho Chi Minh, and Pol Pot, documenting with meticulous evidence a total of 85,000,000 murders perpetrated so that the communists could gain and hold on to power.  In comparison, only about 10,000,000 such crimes can be attributed to Hitler.  This book may not be permitted in the United States.  I am trying to get a French copy.<br><br>

